    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-12T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-12T19:00:00-05:00" n="835"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d835">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.6212 A/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-12T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 12, 1928—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Department handed German Ambassador March 12 a draft of a proposed treaty of
                    arbitration between the United States and Germany. The provisions of the draft
                    are identical in effect with those of the arbitration treaty recently signed
                    with France<note n="3" xml:id="d835fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_816">p. 816</ref>.</note> and
                    with draft arbitration treaties already submitted to the Spanish,. British,
                    Japanese, Italian and Norwegian Governments.<note n="4" xml:id="d835fn4">For
                        negotiations with Great Britain, see <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_945">pp. 945</ref> ff; with Italy, Japan, and Spain, see
                            <ref target="frus1928v03#pg_102">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp.
                            102</ref> ff., <ref target="frus1928v03#pg_135">pp. 135</ref> ff., and
                            <ref target="frus1928v03#pg_879">pp. 879</ref> ff. Although negotiations
                        with Norway were instituted in 1928, the treaty was not signed until 1929
                        (Department of State Treaty Series No. 788).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Department also handed to the Ambassador draft of treaty of similar purport to
                    the so-called Bryan Treaties.<note n="5" xml:id="d835fn5">For index references
                        to the Bryan treaties, see <ref target="frus1914#pg_1130">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914, p. 1130</ref>; <ref
                            target="frus1915#pg_1328">1915, p. 1328</ref>; <ref
                            target="frus1916#pg_1007">1916, p. 1007</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The text of these proposed treaties will be forwarded in next pouch.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d835fn6">Draft treaties not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
